    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "bf66f9276f71ec55",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "bf66f9276f71ec55",
        "text": "Bringing something that is there here follows the elementary shape of movement that repeatedly constitutes the process of collecting. When in the following fourth part of my descriptive enterprise I make stations of fetching the subject, then the analytical attention is directed to selected segments of the fetching loop, which for its part is a constitutive part of the collecting whole. In three enlargements of sections, I examine what is done and what happens at decisive points of this back-and-forth movement.\nThe first of three places where it can become delicate, dangerous, even deadly, is here. What happens here and what do I do here before I go and when I go to get something as a collector? There it is about mental and active preparations as well as about precautions for the time of my absence and my return; and it is about how the difficulties of going away are mastered by rituals of taking leave.\nThe second place is there in the distance: What happens there and what do I do there when I go there, take something and start the way back with it? Problems of taking, holding and carrying lead to a small phenomenology of the bag. Furthermore, it is presented how and why the conversion that initiates the return can fail and what precautions and measures we take against it. It is not by chance that this theme reminds us of what in Gnosticism and Neoplatonism is called a turn or turnaround (epistrophe); for in this mystical philosophy, too, the dispersed many must return to the One from which it had emerged in order to gather in Him. In this process, the conversion at a distance is the decisive turning point.\nThe third place is again here-, locally the same place as the first, but temporally and qualitatively another. What happens here and what do I do here when I come back with what I bring with me, and what after I come back? First, the phases in which the reunion takes place are presented in detail; and then comes the enjoyment: what I have brought is eaten together; what I know to tell is heard together. In this way the group of wild beavers finds ways of renewal and affirmation of their togetherness, from which we still live today.\nIf in the following often the description of > archaic < and the \"modern behavioral figures and forms of experience overlap and blend with each other - not least in examples from economic and aesthetic collecting - this interference tries to do justice to the fact that on the one hand our actions and experiences move in types and schemes, in styles and institutions that we have already acquired in hunter-gatherer times, and that, on the other hand, these forms have emerged in primordial scenes - such as looking at each other, turning away from each other, turning around - that still occur in our reality and from which, if we did not already have them, we would or could form them again. Describing these scenes, situations, constellations can sometimes enable us to understand the meaning of those figures and forms anew."
