        "id": "1f381df468a77f44",
        "text": "The second place is there in the distance: What happens there and what do I do there when I go there, take something and start the way back with it? Problems of taking, holding and carrying lead to a small phenomenology of the bag. Furthermore, it is presented how and why the conversion that initiates the return can fail and what precautions and measures we take against it. It is not by chance that this theme reminds us of what in Gnosticism and Neoplatonism is called a turn or turnaround (epistrophe); for in this mystical philosophy, too, the dispersed many must return to the One from which it had emerged in order to gather in Him. In this process, the conversion at a distance is the decisive turning point.\n"
